ive. Remember, good\\\\r\\\\nmental status in the difficult times may win you the battle more easily!\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nIn the end, I would like to sum up by sharing some messages for people\\\\r\\\\nin isolation; To keep their **mind and body** healthy. Stay connected\\\\r\\\\nand maintain your social networks. Try as much as possible to keep your\\\\r\\\\npersonal daily routines or create new routines if circumstances change.\\\\r\\\\nIf health authorities have recommended limiting your physical social\\\\r\\\\ncontact to contain the outbreak, you can stay connected via telephone,\\\\r\\\\ne-mail, social media or video conference. During times of stress, pay\\\\r\\\\nattention to your own needs and feelings. Engage in healthy activities\\\\r\\\\nthat you enjoy and find relaxing. Exercise regularly, keep regular sleep\\\\r\\\\nroutines and eat healthy food. Keep things in perspective. Public health\\\\r\\\\nagencies and experts in all countries are working on the outbreak to\\\\r\\\\nensure the availability of the best care to those affected. A\\\\r\\\\nnear-constant stream of news reports about an outbreak can cause anyone\\\\r\\\\nto feel anxious or distressed. Seek information updates and practical\\\\r\\\\nguidance at specific times during the day from health professionals and\\\\r\\\\nWHO website and avoid listening to or following rumours that make you\\\\r\\\\nfeel uncomfortable.\\\\r\\\\n\"},{\"title\":\"Routine During Lockdown\",\"slug\":\"routine-during-lockdown\",\"content\":\"**STRATEGIES AND EVERYDAY LIFE ROUTINES TO ADOPT DURING\\\\r\\\\nLOCKDOWN/SELF-ISOLATION TO COPE WITH STRESS CAUSED BY COVID 19**\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nSince the World Health Organization declared the COVID-19 outbreak a\\\\r\\\\nglobal pandemic, many of us, even those who have not been infected by\\\\r\\\\nthe virus, will choose to quarantine in our homes for the upcoming\\\\r\\\\nweeks. These can be difficult times for all of us as we hear about\\\\r\\\\nspread of COVID-19 from all over the world, through television, social\\\\r\\\\nmedia, newspapers, family and friends and other sources. The most common\\\\r\\\\nemotion faced by all is \\'fear\\'. It makes us anxious, panicky and can\\\\r\\\\neven possibly make us think, say or do things that we might not consider\\\\r\\\\nappropriate under normal circumstances.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nLet us first try to understand some terms related to the present\\\\r\\\\nscenario.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n**Social distancing** refers to certain measures taken to stop or slow\\\\r\\\\ndown the spread of highly contagious diseases which include limiting\\\\r\\\\nlarge gatherings, closing down public buildings such as schools,\\\\r\\\\nuniversities, cancelling public events, etc.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n**Quarantine** is defined as the separation of people who have been\\\\r\\\\nexposed to a contagious disease to ascertain whether they become sick,\\\\r\\\\nthereby reducing the risk of them infecting others. Governments use\\\\r\\\\nquarantines to stop the spread of contagious diseases. Quarantines are\\\\r\\\\nfor people or groups who don\\'t have symptoms but were exposed to the\\\\r\\\\nsickness. A quarantine keeps them away from others so they don\\'t\\\\r\\\\nunknowingly infect anyone.\\xa0\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nQuarantines may be used during **outbreaks (**sudden rise in the number\\\\r\\\\nof cases of a disease), **epidemics (s**imilar to outbreaks, but\\\\r\\\\ngenerally considered larger and more widespread), or **pandemics\\\\r\\\\n(**larger than epidemics, generally global in nature and affect more\\\\r\\\\npeople).\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n**Isolation**, in contrast, is where a person diagnosed to have a\\\\r\\\\ncontagious disease is separated from the general population, to avoid\\\\r\\\\ntransmission of the disease to healthy people. While isolation serves\\\\r\\\\nthe same purpose as quarantine, it\\'s reserved for those who are already\\\\r\\\\nsick. It keeps *infected* people away from healthy people to prevent the\\\\r\\\\nsickness from spreading.\\xa0\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nPresently, governments across the world, including India, are using a\\\\r\\\\ncombination of these measures to stop the spread of the COVID-19\\\\r\\\\npandemic.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nBased on studies from previous epidemics/pandemics, we shall identify\\\\r\\\\nsome of the mental health concerns which people in quarantine face and\\\\r\\\\npropose solutions/remedial measures for the same. Now let\\'s discuss a\\\\r\\\\nfew tips that we can follow to keep away anxiety and stress;\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n**As we know, Exercise** reduces levels of cortisol, which is a stress\\\\r\\\\nhormone, and regular exercise is even more important now that you find\\\\r\\\\nyourself in self-isolation. Being at home almost all the time, abiding\\\\r\\\\nby the national lockdown, we all are prone to a sedentary lifestyle.\\\\r\\\\nHence working out at home becomes even more essential at this point of\\\\r\\\\ntime. When you move your body your heart pumps your white blood cells,\\\\r\\\\nyour immune defence, to all parts of the body which gives them a chance\\\\r\\\\nto do their job and scan the whole body for anything foreign.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n**Another important aspect to keep in mind is getting adequate sleep.**\\\\r\\\\nPoor sleep is linked to an increased risk of heart disease which is\\\\r\\\\nreason enough to aim for 7-8 hours\\' sleep a night. We also have a type\\\\r\\\\nof white blood cell called T-cells and research has shown that not\\\\r\\\\ngetting proper sleep prevents our T-cells from being able to fight\\\\r\\\\ninfection. Sleep also helps our body rest, restore and recover. Stress\\\\r\\\\nand anxiety can cause sleep problems but there are some simple steps we\\\\r\\\\ncan take to help improve the quality of our sleep. Focusing on eating a\\\\r\\\\nwell-balanced diet and daily exercise can also help.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nNext thing to consider is if we have the habit of **smoking**, then we\\\\r\\\\nneed to reduce or stop it, because smoking puts our body at an increased\\\\r\\\\nrisk of developing both viral and bacterial infections. By smoking one\\\\r\\\\nis already challenging his/her lungs and COVID-19 is a respiratory\\\\r\\\\ndisease meaning it affects the health of our lungs. Therefore, it is\\\\r\\\\nrecommended to quit smoking for our heart health as well as to protect\\\\r\\\\nour immune system.\\xa0\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n**One more important precautionary measure would be to reduce alcohol\\\\r\\\\nintake, if any.** A glass of wine or two might commonly be used to help\\\\r\\\\nmanage feelings of stress, but alcohol can weaken our immune system. In\\\\r\\\\ntimes like these, it is recommended to reduce our alcohol intake and opt\\\\r\\\\nfor sleep, exercise and healthy food to combat stress and anxiety.\\xa0\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nWhile it might seem like the world is only talking about one topic right\\\\r\\\\nnow, enforced social isolation could also provide the perfect\\\\r\\\\nopportunity for many people to take a break from the news cycle. We\\\\r\\\\ncould actually focus on things that we usually do not get time for, like\\\\r\\\\ngardening, cooking, pickling, puzzles, craft, sewing, learning to\\\\r\\\\nmeditate, building furniture, reading books and so on. Now could be the\\\\r\\\\nperfect time to do them all, or some, or half of a few --- whatever one\\\\r\\\\ncan manage.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nAlso, the WHO has advised, to \\\\\\\\\\\\\"draw on skills you have used in the past\\\\r\\\\nthat have helped you manage previous adversities.\\\\\\\\\\\\\" So we can try\\\\r\\\\nfocussing on such activities.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n**Peggy Whitson (The first female commander of the International Space\\\\r\\\\nStation (ISS), who has spent a cumulative total of 665 days in space,\\\\r\\\\nwhich includes two six-month tours of duty), says that while on the ISS,\\\\r\\\\nshe would do things she\\'d been thinking about doing if she had more\\\\r\\\\ntime, and recommends people s