\\n> more\\xa0[optimistic](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/optimism)\\xa0and\\\\r\\\\n> joyful mindset, even in the face\\\\r\\\\n> of\\xa0[stress](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/stress)\\xa0and\\\\r\\\\n> loss. For many, this can be difficult, and you should not expect to\\\\r\\\\n> magically change your thoughts and feelings. But, the more you see,\\\\r\\\\n> think, and do that reflects\\\\r\\\\n> peace,\\xa0[happiness](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/happiness),\\\\r\\\\n> and positivity, the more it can influence your mood and outlook.\\\\r\\\\n>\\\\r\\\\n> **2)VOLUNTEER FOR HELP-**\\\\r\\\\n>\\\\r\\\\n> If you\\'re feeling powerless and hopeless, remember that you can do\\\\r\\\\n> your part to wash your hands, resist the urge to hoard unnecessarily,\\\\r\\\\n> stay home unless absolutely necessary, and encourage others to do the\\\\r\\\\n> same. It may not feel like superhero-level work, but it is\\\\r\\\\n> superhero-level work to protect your neighbors and those most\\\\r\\\\n> vulnerable. Your seemingly small efforts add up and make a tremendous\\\\r\\\\n> impact on your community. They add up. They mean something. Keep\\\\r\\\\n> moving forward, and together we\\'re going to all come out of this.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nThe simplest thing everyone can do right now is look out for their\\\\r\\\\nneighbours and offer help with shopping and other errands. If you must\\\\r\\\\nstay at home but feel well enough to help, you can volunteer remotely,\\\\r\\\\nfor example to befriend people who are isolated people or share official\\\\r\\\\ninformation, such as from\\\\r\\\\nthe\\xa0[[government]{.underline}](https://www.gov.uk/coronavirus),by\\\\r\\\\ntelephone or online.\\xa0\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nIt\\\\\\\\\\'s not just about neighbours who are shielding, self-isolating or\\\\r\\\\nphysically distancing from others. Other people in the community who\\\\r\\\\nmight also appreciate help are:\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n-   stretched medical staff and volunteers\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n-   staff and volunteers in key worker roles\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n-   supermarket workers\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n-   delivery drivers.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n**3)STAY VIRTUALLY CONNECTED WITH FRIENDS AND FAMILY-**\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nWhile the\\xa0[World Health\\\\r\\\\nOrganization](https://twitter.com/WHO/status/1242123569146089472)\\xa0makes\\\\r\\\\nclear why we need to stay away from one another, confining yourself to\\\\r\\\\nhome is no easy task. Loneliness is already a\\xa0[social health crisis\\\\r\\\\nitself](https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2018/07/loneliness-is-contagious-and-heres-how-to-beat-it),\\\\r\\\\nwith roughly 1 in 3 adults experiencing it to some degree. Staying\\\\r\\\\nvirtually connected to your closed ones is highly essential to make them\\\\r\\\\nfeel less depressed. Atleast they would think that they have somebody to\\\\r\\\\nrely on during this crisis. Thankfully, in the world of modern\\\\r\\\\ntechnology there are still ways to virtually stay connected to family,\\\\r\\\\nfriends and loved ones during this period.Social media, phone calls,\\\\r\\\\nSkype, Google Hangouts and FaceTime are tried and true methods of\\\\r\\\\nstaying connected.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nThe COVID-19 situation is emotionally taxing so it\\'s important to make\\\\r\\\\nthe time to stay virtually connected to friends and family.Schedule some\\\\r\\\\nchill-out time to let your mind take a break and enjoy a group Netflix\\\\r\\\\nsession without stress.Play some of your favourite music and discover\\\\r\\\\nnew artists with friends or even people from across the world.Video\\\\r\\\\nchat, play games, manage your stress with meditation or exercise and\\\\r\\\\ncheck in regularly with loved ones.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n> **4)ADVOCATE FACTS REGARDING TO COVID-19-**\\\\r\\\\n>\\\\r\\\\n> We should keep us updated about the various advocacy updates .For\\\\r\\\\n> example we have seen that there has been a drastic impact on women of\\\\r\\\\n> our society.\\\\r\\\\n>\\\\r\\\\n> **Emerging Gender Impacts During the Pandemic-**\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n-   **Exacerbated burdens of unpaid care work on women and girls**:\\\\r\\\\n    > Where healthcare systems are stretched by efforts to contain\\\\r\\\\n    > outbreaks, care responsibilities are frequently \\\\\"downloaded\\\\\" onto\\\\r\\\\n    > women and girls, who usually bear responsibility for caring for\\\\r\\\\n    > ill family members and the elderly. The closure of schools further\\\\r\\\\n    > exacerbates the burden of unpaid care work on women and girls, who\\\\r\\\\n    > absorb the additional work of caring for children.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n-   **Meeting the needs of women healthcare workers**: Women constitute\\\\r\\\\n    > 70 per cent of the workers in the health and social sector\\\\r\\\\n    > globally, and are on the frontlines of the response. Within this\\\\r\\\\n    > sector, an average gender pay gap of 28 per cent exists, which may\\\\r\\\\n    > be exacerbated in times of crises. Women healthcare workers have\\\\r\\\\n    > called attention to their specific needs beyond personal\\\\r\\\\n    > protective equipment, including to meet menstrual hygiene needs.\\\\r\\\\n    > Psychosocial support should also be provided to frontline\\\\r\\\\n    > responders.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n**5)OUR RESPONSE IF SOMEONE GETS SICK WITH THE DISEASE-**\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nIf a member of a household becomes sick, the best practice for everyone\\\\r\\\\nin the household is to stay home for 14 days and keep track of any\\\\r\\\\nsymptoms they experience. Anytime another member of the household begins\\\\r\\\\nshowing signs of illness, they should assume it\\\\\\\\\\'s COVID-19 and begin\\\\r\\\\nisolating themselves too.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\"If a healthy family member must go to work or buy groceries for their\\\\r\\\\nfamily, they need to take extra precautions by checking their\\\\r\\\\ntemperature before leaving the house, wearing a mask while out and\\\\r\\\\nwashing their hands with soap and water before leaving home.\\\\\\\\\\\\\" If\\\\r\\\\nsomeone in the house shows signs of illness, they should social distance\\\\r\\\\nfrom their family as much as possible by remaining in a separate room\\\\r\\\\nand using their own bathroom, wearing a mask and staying home.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n> **6)COMMUNITY RESILIENCE-**\\\\r\\\\n>\\\\r\\\\n> The Covid-19 pandemic has unimaginably affected social, economic,\\\\r\\\\n> institutional and governance settings worldwide. It has generated an\\\\r\\\\n> unparalleled health crisis affecting thousands of people, forcing over\\\\r\\\\n> 3 billion people to be locked at home. While the adverse and wholesome\\\\r\\\\n> impact of Covid-19 is yet to be measured, in this entire catastrophic\\\\r\\\\n> scenario, the poor, vulnerable, low social and low income groups and\\\\r\\\\n> informal sectors in India are the worst affected in multitude\\\\r\\\\n> ways.Even the food supply has become low.\\\\r\\\\n>\\\\r\\\\n> So as a member of our community it is our duty to\\xa0 use available\\\\r\\\\n> resources\\\\r\\\\n> ([energy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Energy),\\xa0[communication](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communication),\\xa0[transportation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transportation),\\xa0[food](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Food),\\\\r\\\\n> etc.) to respond to, withstand, and recover from adverse situations\\\\r\\\\n> (e.g.\\xa0[economic\\\\r\\\\n> collapse](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_collapse)\\xa0to\\xa0[global\\\\r\\\\n> catastrophic\\\\r\\\\n> risks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_catastrophic_risks)).\\xa0This\\\\r\\\\n> allows for the adaptation and growth of a community after disaster\\\\r\\\\n> strikes.[^\\\\\\\\[2\\\\\\\\]^](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Community_resilience#cite_note-2)\\xa0Communities\\\\r\\\\n> that are resilient are able to minimize\\\\r\\\\n> any\\xa0[disaster](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disaster), making the\\\\r\\\\n> return to normal life as effortless as possible. By implementing a\\\\r\\\\n> community resilience plan, we can come together and overcome any\\\\r\\\\n> disaster, while rebuilding physically and economically.\\\\r\\\\n>\\\\r\\\\n> **7)CLAP FOR KEY WORKERS-**\\\\r\\\\n>\\\\r\\\\n> Clapping for the key workers which includes doctors, nurses,\\\\r\\\\n> sanitizing workers, policemen, security guards, administrative workers\\\\r\\\\n> etc is a way of appreciating their endless efforts and the pain they\\\\r\\\\n> are going through to keep us safe and secure during this pandemic.\\\\r\\\\n> This small token of appreciation and love can encourage them and will\\\\r\\\\n> also improve their mental peace. Being grateful has repeatedly been\\\\r\\\\n> shown to boost wellbeing and promote prosocial behaviour. Neuroscience\\\\r\\\\n> has shown that the human voice has an important impact, reducing\\\\r\\\\n> stress hormones and raising levels of the \\\\\"cuddle hormone\\\\\" oxytocin.\\\\r\\\\n> In fact, research shows that a mother\\'s voice can offer similar\\\\r\\\\n> comfort to giving an actual hug.\\\\r\\\\n>\\\\r\\\\n> What clapping with our neighbours did for many of you, was to provide\\\\r\\\\n> a powerful, emotional and physical reminder that that we are part of\\\\r\\\\n> something bigger and for once it feels as though we are all on the\\\\r\\\\n> same side.\\\\r\\\\n\"},{\"title\":\"Reliable source For COVID News\",\"slug\":\"reliable-source-for-covid-news\",\"content\":\"**[COVID 19 IN THE NEWS,RELIABLE SOURCES-]{.underline}**\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nThe news around COVID-19 is changing rapidly and we are seeing a lot of\\\\r\\\\nmisinformation being shared.\\xa0 This guide aims to point you to reliable\\\\r\\\\nsources of news and health information on COVID-19. Having access to\\\\r\\\\ncredible information sources, having media information literacy skills\\\\r\\\\nand ability to control emotional reaction are crucial tools to have all\\\\r\\\\nof us prepared and ready to affront this critical situation linked to\\\\r\\\\nCOVID-19 spread.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nAs COVID-19 cases have surged across the globe, so has\\\\r\\\\nmisinformation.\\xa0[According\\\\r\\\\nto](https://members.tortoisemedia.com/2020/03/23/the-infodemic-fake-news-coronavirus/content.html)\\xa0research\\\\r\\\\n, every day in March 2020 an average of 46,000 new posts on Twitter\\\\r\\\\nlinked to inaccurate or misleading information about the crisis. The\\\\r\\\\nrapidly changing situation means that people are naturally\\xa0[grasping for\\\\r\\\\ninformation](https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/business/media/stat-news-boston-coronavirus.html)\\xa0about\\\\r\\\\nthe pandemic. So what\\'s the best way to separate the trustworthy from\\\\r\\\\nthe fake?\\xa0\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nLET US TALK ABOUT SOME COMMON QUESTIONS ON THIS TOPIC-\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n#### **Q)** How do you know whether a news source is trustworthy?\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nIf the source isn\\'t one you\\'re familiar with, then Google it to make\\\\r\\\\nsure it is a legitimate news organization. The\\xa0[site \\\\\"Media Bias/Fact\\\\r\\\\nCheck\\\\\"](https://mediabiasfactcheck.com/)\\xa0rates various news\\\\r\\\\norganizations on \\\\\"factual reporting\\\\\" as well as ideological skew. Major\\\\r\\\\nhealth organizations such as the Centers for Disease Control and\\\\r\\\\nPrevention (CDC) and World Health Organization (WHO) are among the most\\\\r\\\\ncredible sources of information on the COVID-19 pandemic.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nOnce you\\'ve made sure that the news source is reliable, check out the\\\\r\\\\nauthor. Consider whether the writer is a coronavirus or pandemic expert\\\\r\\\\nor just a scientist in a related field. If the author is a journalist,\\\\r\\\\ncheck to see what their usual beat is. Is this a health reporter with\\\\r\\\\nexperience covering scientific topics?\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nAnother rule of thumb: \\\\\"Don\\'t just rely on one source\\\\\". Instead,\\\\r\\\\npractice what communication scholars call \\\\\"lateral reading\\\\\" and\\xa0gather\\\\r\\\\ninformation from a variety of diverse news sources. If a certain\\\\r\\\\nconclusion\\xa0appears repeatedly in different reliable sources, that should\\\\r\\\\nincrease your confidence in it.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n#### Q) **How do I make sure the information in a report is legitimate? What are red flags to watch out for?**\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nCheck when the story was published.Especially for COVID-19 \\\\\\\\[news\\\\\\\\], the\\\\r\\\\ndate matters so much,, because \\\\\"a lot of the facts on the ground may\\\\r\\\\nhave changed,\\\\\" like case counts.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nTry to determine\\xa0*where\\xa0*the information presented is coming from. Is it\\\\r\\\\nfrom a state epidemiologist, the CDC or another trusted organization? If\\\\r\\\\nthere\\'s a link to the source, click on that link to double-check the\\\\r\\\\ndata yourself. The \\\\\"click the links\\\\\" rule also applies to scrolling past\\\\r\\\\nheadlines on social media: Read the article before you share.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n\\\\\"Take a deep breath and be skeptical, especially when you see the\\\\r\\\\nfollowing red flags: too-good-to-be-true headlines or news that plays\\\\r\\\\nstrongly to emotional cues instead of taking a level-headed approach.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n####  \\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\nIf you realize you\\'ve already shared misinformation, you should\\\\r\\\\nself-correct, ideally by deleting the original, inaccurate statement and\\\\r\\\\ncreate a new post, email or text---whichever platform you originally\\\\r\\\\nshared it on---with the accurate information. Alternatively, you can\\\\r\\\\nprominently update your original post with the correction, although\\\\r\\\\npeople may not see the updated version on their feeds. Plus, thank the\\\\r\\\\nfriend who tipped you off to the error.\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n#### YOU MUST BE WONDERING WHAT ARE SOME RELIABLE SOUCES-\\\\r\\\\n\\\\r\\\\n#### SO here is a list of Expert-recommended re